# Main thesis

[D2.0]: Disclosure 2.0 is the natural extension of the clinical-AI transparency lineage to agentic-LLM research; the published unit becomes a six-item manifest (prompts, model identifier, commit history, reviewer-subagent transcripts, audit log, tagged release) at a tagged DOI release.
  + <Lineage>
  + <Gap>
  + <Self-demo>
  - <Determinism>
  - <Self-audit>
  - <Hallucinating reviewers>
  - <Equity>
  - <Audit hallucination>
  - <Selective lineage>
  - <Analogy stretch>
  - <Model Cards precedence>

# Supporting arguments

<Lineage>: A five-year sequence of clinical-AI transparency standards establishes the disclosure-unit pattern; Disclosure 2.0 completes the sequence for the agentic-LLM class.

(1) [Sendak2020]: Model Facts Labels (Sendak et al. 2020) name the disclosure unit for a deployed clinical ML model.
(2) [CONSORT-AI]: The 2020 CONSORT-AI / SPIRIT-AI extensions name it for AI-intervention RCTs.
(3) [TRIPOD-AI]: TRIPOD+AI (Collins et al. 2024) names it for AI-enabled prediction-model reporting.
(4) [Pattern]: Each standard atomises an artefact type (deployed model, trial, prediction model) and binds journal-side adoption to author-side compliance.
-----
(5) [D2.0]

<Gap>: The lineage's standards assume the disclosed unit is a model or a trial; agentic LLMs produce neither.

(1) [CoScientist]: Co-Scientist (Nature 2026) autonomously generates and refines biomedical hypotheses; AML drug-repurposing candidates were in vitro validated.
(2) [AIScientist]: Sakana AI Scientist (Nature 2026) produced a manuscript that passed first-round blind workshop peer review.
(3) [No artefact match]: Neither system produces a fixed predictive model with stable weights, nor a clinical trial.
(4) [Policy lag]: Current biomedical-journal AI policies prohibit-by-default and ask for a single-sentence acknowledgement; prohibition without an audit surface invites camouflage.
-----
(5) [D2.0]

<Self-demo>: The present Perspective is itself produced under Disclosure 2.0; the case study returned a preregistered NULL and the Layer-2 audit filed 12 substantive findings on the case-study manuscript.

(1) [Repo public]: MIT-licensed repo at tag viewpoint-npjdm-v1.0.0; every manifest item present.
(2) [Null preserved]: Layer 3 delta-C-index = 0.006 [-0.008, 0.030], primary hypothesis not rejected, n=333.
(3) [Audit preserved]: Layer 2 filed 1 blocker + 2 high + 9 medium-low findings; within-Layer-1 reviewer rounds did not catch them.
(4) [Findability is the test]: A standard that surfaces its own failure modes is the strongest available demonstration.
(5) [Limits acknowledged]: Disclosure 2.0 does not eliminate failure modes — only makes them findable; single case study is not scale evidence.
-----
(6) [D2.0]

# Counter-arguments and rebuttals

<Determinism>: LLMs are not bit-deterministic; the prompt is not a protocol.
  - <Distributional reproducibility>

<Distributional reproducibility>: Same prompt + model id + snapshot + tool envelope must yield the same selected sub-claim and statistical method across three runs; the headline effect size within the original's bootstrap 95% interval.

<Self-audit>: A single operator cannot audit himself.
  - <Sealed Layer 2>

<Sealed Layer 2>: Layer 2 is dispatched as a sealed audit subagent; Layer 3 is preregistered before Layer 1 sees the data; reviewer personas are diversified; repository is open to third-party re-audit; seal is testimonial rather than cryptographic.

<Hallucinating reviewers>: Reviewer subagents hallucinate the way the pipeline does.
  - <Failure preservation>

<Failure preservation>: The hallucination is preserved verbatim and the resolution lives in subsequent commits, making the failure mode catchable rather than camouflaged.

<Equity>: This proposal is for well-resourced submitters only — clinicians without git fluency or institutional compute cannot meet the full manifest.
  - <Minimum viable manifest>

<Minimum viable manifest>: Items 1, 2, 3, 6 of the manifest preserve the consequential audit surfaces at near-zero infrastructure cost.

<Audit hallucination>: The audit subagent runs the same model class as Layer 1; Layer 2 hallucinates too.
  - <Cross-model audit>

<Cross-model audit>: Layer 1 on one vendor + Layer 2 on a different vendor is the proposed mitigation; the manifest's models array supports declaration; same-vendor audit treated as single-rater study.

# New issues surfaced by the npj DM lineage reframe (patched in v1.0.1)

<Selective lineage>: The lineage selects Sendak 2020, CONSORT-AI 2020 and TRIPOD+AI 2024 but skips CLAIM 2024, DECIDE-AI 2022, STANDING Together 2024, and the WAME / ICMJE 2024 AI guidance.
  - <Selection criteria>

<Selection criteria>: Three standards are cited because each names a distinct artefact type (deployed model, trial, prediction model); the omitted standards are either imaging-modality-specific (CLAIM), decision-support-specific (DECIDE-AI), reporting-equity-specific (STANDING Together), or generic publication-ethics rather than artefact-disclosure (WAME / ICMJE). [PATCHED in v1.0.1 — one-sentence rationale added to Section 1.]

<Analogy stretch>: Disclosure 2.0 items are claimed to be "analogous to" Model Facts Labels fields, but Model Facts Labels disclose deployment-time properties whereas Disclosure 2.0 discloses process-time properties — different temporal locus.
  - <Temporal locus is the gap>

<Temporal locus is the gap>: The temporal-locus mismatch IS the gap the Perspective identifies; the lineage's standards cover model-at-deployment (Model Facts Labels) and design-time (CONSORT-AI, TRIPOD+AI), but no standard covers process-as-it-runs. Disclosure 2.0 fills that locus. [PATCHED in v1.0.1 — temporal-locus distinction stated explicitly in Section 3.]

<Model Cards precedence>: Mitchell et al. 2019 "Model Cards for Model Reporting" (FAccT) preceded Sendak 2020 by a year and is the actual mother paper of the lineage; not citing it weakens the historical claim.
  - <Sendak operationalises Mitchell>

<Sendak operationalises Mitchell>: Mitchell 2019 was a general ML framework; Sendak 2020 operationalised it for clinical deployment with a one-page Model Facts Label tied to a real implementation. [PATCHED in v1.0.1 — Mitchell 2019 added as ref #12 and Section 1 attributes Sendak as operationalisation.]

# Concrete recommendation (pilot)

[Pilot]: npj Digital Medicine should pilot Disclosure 2.0 as an alternative submission track for AI-deep manuscripts; 5-10 submissions/quarter, 90 days, no Editorial Manager feature work needed.
  + [D2.0]
  + <Editorial Manager fit>: PDF manifest alongside cover letter + linked Zenodo DOI; editorial office validates against JSON schema.
  + <Outcome metric>: Pilot success is whether the manifest is CONSULTED by reviewers, not just published.

